Beyond the well-known effects of ultraviolet light, long-term exposure to blue light with short wavelengths may alter the ocular surface by three main mechanisms: oxidative stress damage, ocular surface inflammation, and cell apoptosis [4, 5, 36–40] (Table 2). These can increase the ocular phototoxicity of blue light in subjects with dry eyes or contribute to the development and pathogenesis of dry eyes [5].Table 2
